UPDATE designers SET biography = E'Founded in 2015, Atelier Février is a Franco-Nepalese house devoted to the art of hand-knotted rugs. The atelier was born from the meeting of its two founders — French designer Florian Pretet and Nepalese entrepreneur Lisa Mukhia Pretet — in Kathmandu, where Florian had spent thirteen years managing cashmere and pashmina production for Hermès.\n\nFlorian, a graduate of the Parisian fashion school Studio Berçot, had always been a compulsive draughtsman. Lisa, raised between Darjeeling and Kathmandu, brought an intimate knowledge of Nepal''s artisan workshops and a sharp entrepreneurial instinct. They named their venture after the month they first met.\n\nhttps://www.atelierfevrier.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/Atelier-feb-24-151-scaled.jpg | small\n\nEvery rug begins as an elaborate pencil sketch by Florian, whose designs draw on fashion, nature, street life and art — informed by a childhood spent alongside an artist father. Each sketch is then scaled up and translated by hand into knotted wool, silk and hemp by expert weavers in Nepal, a process requiring more than fifty people and three to six months to complete.\n\n<strong>''Tous nos tapis semblent vivants et animés grâce à un jeu de texture et de mouvement. Il arrive que l''inspiration soit la même, mais l''expression est toujours différente.''</strong> — Lisa Mukhia Pretet, De Fil en Déco interview, 2024 <em>''All our rugs seem alive and animated through a play of texture and movement. The inspiration may be the same, but the expression is always different.''</em>\n\nThe rugs are made of premium Tibetan wool — rich in lanolin, which protects the fibre and makes each piece more beautiful with age — combined with the finest Chinese silk for added lustre and durability. Atelier Février requires a minimum of 100 knots per square inch, with the most intricate designs reaching considerably higher densities. As Architectural Digest observed, ''the precise geometry of a diagonally edged rug of tonal chevrons is startling, while a nearly three-dimensional landscape of undulating boxes boasts the disconcerting optic power of an M. C. Escher woodcut.''\n\nhttps://www.atelierfevrier.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/Atelier-feb-24-106-scaled.jpg | left\n\nCurving — the technique of sculpting the wool to create undulations and height effects — is a signature element, lending each piece a sculptural, three-dimensional quality that sets Atelier Février apart. Their Nazar design, first presented at Maison & Objet in 2016, became their calling card; each iteration is drawn by hand, ensuring no two are ever identical.\n\nAtelier Février is committed to fair-trade standards and uses exclusively natural fibres and dyes. The atelier is a certified partner of Label STEP, the Swiss fair-trade foundation for handmade carpets. Today their rugs can be found in projects by leading interior architects including Tristan Auers.' WHERE slug = 'atelier-fevrier-isha-mukhia-pretet-and-florian-pretet'